### @import

**@import** includes styles from another CSS file.

---

### Basic Syntax

```css
@import url('reset.css');
@import url('style.css');
```

---

### With Media Queries

```css
@import url('mobile.css') screen and (max-width: 767px);
@import url('print.css') print;
@import url('dark.css') (prefers-color-scheme: dark);
```

---

### With Supports

```css
@import url('grid.css') supports(display: grid);
@import url('flexbox.css') supports(not (display: grid));
```

---

### With Layers

```css
@import url('reset.css') layer(reset);
@import url('components.css') layer(components);
@import url('utilities.css') layer(utilities);
```

---

### Important Rules

1. **Must be at the top** of your CSS file (before any other rules)
2. Multiple `@import` statements are allowed
3. Each `@import` creates an **additional HTTP request**
4. Order matters - later imports override earlier ones

```css
/* CORRECT - at the top */
@import url('reset.css');
@import url('theme.css');

body { /* Styles come after */ }

/* WRONG - imports must come first */
body { margin: 0; }
@import url('reset.css'); /* This will fail */
```

---

### @import vs <link>

```html
<!-- LINK - preferred for production -->
<link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
```

| Feature | @import | <link> |
|---------|---------|--------|
| HTTP requests | Additional | Included |
| Parallel loading | No | Yes |
| Performance | Slower | Faster |
| Modern usage | Rare | Common |

---

> **Best Practice:** Use `<link>` in HTML for production. `@import` can be useful for CSS organization but is slower. Use CSS layers instead for dependency management.
